{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613538"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16315"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16315"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.2,0,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116116"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9006"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98112"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8548"},{"type":"tags","id":"10416"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21436"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116116"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cornea forms the clear, anterior surface of the eyeball and represents the first optical element that light encounters as it enters the eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the cornea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refraction of light","Protection of the retina","Control of pupillary size","Transmission of visual signals","Accommodation of lens"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the cornea is \u003Cstrong\u003Erefraction of light\u003C/strong\u003E. It provides approximately two-thirds of the eye\u0027s total focusing power by bending light rays as they enter the eye so that they can be focused on the retina for clear vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtection of the retina\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary function as the cornea specifically protects the anterior segment rather than the retina directly, though it does provide some protective function. \u003Cstrong\u003EControl of pupillary size\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of the iris, not the cornea. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransmission of visual signals\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the optic nerve which carries electrical impulses to the brain. \u003Cstrong\u003EAccommodation of lens\u003C/strong\u003E is achieved by the ciliary muscles acting on the lens to change its shape for focusing at different distances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cornea must remain transparent and maintain its precise curvature to properly refract light. It contains no blood vessels that might interfere with light transmission and is one of the most sensitive tissues in the body.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The cornea contributes about 66% of the total refractive power of the human eye.","Light rays are focused onto the retina through the cornea\u0027s unique transparent and curved architecture.","The cornea functions as a physical barrier protecting internal ocular structures."],"references":["Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press.","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98112"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16315"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98112"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T15:24:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T15:25:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9006"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116116"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4941"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{